#Text=Read a Dog 's Pedigree
#Text=If you 're the proud owner of a pedigreed dog , it 's important to understand all of the detailed information found on its certificate .
#Text=And if you 're thinking about buying a dog from a breeder , you 'll want to see its pedigree and verify the information found on it .
#Text=The dog 's official name , show titles , and registration number are commonly found on its pedigree .
#Text=The document will also list similar information for the dog 's ancestors .
#Text=It is increasingly common for them to also include DNA and health identification , so make sure to check the certificate for this information , too .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Tracing a Dog 's Lineage
#Text=Find the dog 's registered name and birth date .
#Text=The dog 's official name , as recorded by a kennel or other organization , will definitely appear on the pedigree .
#Text=Usually it will appear as the first name on the left or right corner , along with the date of birth .
#Text=Identify the dog 's ancestors .
#Text=Most of the time , the names of the dog 's parents will be just to the right .
#Text=A pedigree should list the names of both the dam ( mother ) and sire ( father ) .
#Text=Depending on the pedigree , you may also see the dog 's grandparents farther to the right , then the great-grandparents , and so on .
#Text=A proper pedigree should list the official names of all of the ancestors .
#Text=Depending upon the pedigree report and the known ancestry , this could go back for just 3 or 4 generations , or may go back several .
#Text=Determine whether your dog has been inbred , line-bred , or outcrossed .
#Text=Pay attention to the names of the dog and its ancestors .
#Text=If you see repeated names , it is a sign that the ancestors were closely related .
#Text=Breeders maintain and perfect the characteristics associated with particular breeds by carefully selecting which dogs to mate .
#Text=Inbreeding means that very closely related dogs have mated , such as a son and mother , father and daughter , or brother and sister .
#Text=Linebreeding means that a dog 's sire and dam have a close ancestor in common .
#Text=Out crossing occurs when there are no common ancestors in 3 to 4 generations .
#Text=Breeders and owners often highly value inbreeding or linebreeding traced to a notable ancestor .
#Text=Check for DNA numbers .
#Text=Since DNA testing has become easier and more widespread , it is increasingly common for numbers identifying a dog 's genetic makeup to appear on a pedigree .
#Text=If these are available , they should be found next to the dog 's name .
#Text=Each dog whose DNA has been officially tested and registered ( with a kennel , for example ) will have an identifying number .
#Text=Study the stud book numbers .
#Text=A pedigree may also list when a dog was bred , and which of the dam 's litters the dog comes from .
#Text=These are known as stud book numbers .
#Text=If you pay attention to the dam 's birth date , you can also determine how old she was when she had the litter .
#Text=For example , if the dog 's pedigree lists a stud book date of 2/2016 , and the dam 's date of birth is 5/2013 , you can determine that she was not quite 3 years old when she had the litter .
#Text=Interpreting Special Information
#Text=Look for show records .
#Text=If the dog or its ancestors were awarded in any notable competitions , these will probably be listed on the pedigree along with each dog 's name .
#Text=These may simply be recorded as a series of abbreviations .
#Text=For example , you may see the abbreviation “ FCI , ” signifying the Fédération Cynologique Internationale World Championship .
#Text=If you are unfamiliar with any of the abbreviations , ask the breeder or kennel association to explain .
#Text=Decode any title abbreviations .
#Text=Many breeds can be awarded special titles that recognize highly desirable traits .
#Text=These can vary from breed to breed , and can be difficult to interpret unless you are very familiar with the breed .
#Text=Just ask the breeder or kennel association to explain if you are n't sure what the titles mean .
#Text=The pedigree for a German Shepherd , for example , may list titles for things like tracking , herding , and obedience .
#Text=The titles may appear simply as abbreviations , however , like “ BH , ” “ FH2 , ” and “ SchH2 . ”
#Text=You can check the websites of organizations like the American Kennel Club and the United Kennel Club for lists of common title and show award abbreviations .
#Text=You can also ask your breeder or use their website to help you identify titles or acronyms that may be common in your dog 's breed .
#Text=Study any health information .
#Text=Thanks to DNA testing and careful breeding records , pedigrees can include information about any health issues that are a concern for a dog 's breed .
#Text=This information can include whether or not a dog and its ancestors have been tested for genetic diseases that are known to be a problem for the breed .
#Text=Health characteristics may be listed along with each dog 's name and other identifying information , or separately .
#Text=Recognizing Certifications
#Text=Verify that the pedigree has an official seal .
#Text=Pedigrees contain quite a bit of information that can determine a dog 's value , eligibility for competitions , etc.
#Text=Certification from a recognized kennel association , such as the AKC ( American Kennel Club ) helps prove that the pedigree is accurate and trustworthy .
#Text=If you plan to show or breed your dog in the future , you will need these records .
#Text=Keep them on file , and make sure you get the most accurate , up-to-date reports for these purposes .
#Text=Double-check the registration number .
#Text=If the pedigree is certified by a kennel association , it will include an official number identifying the dog .
#Text=Contact the association and ask to cross-check the number .
#Text=They may also be able to confirm other information found on the pedigree so that you can verify its accuracy and legitimacy .
#Text=Do n't be alarmed by a conditional registration .
#Text=Some pedigrees may be marked as “ conditional ” if DNA information shows there is an unknown ancestor .
#Text=This does not necessarily mean that the dog cannot be considered purebred .
#Text=The kennel association may also allow the conditional status to be removed after a certain number of generations .
#Text=Conditional pedigrees may have a different seal or coloring to identify them as such .
#Text=Check to see if your dog 's pedigree is registered .
#Text=Not all breeders will pay the fees to register a dog for you .
#Text=Your AKC paperwork may be accurate , but not active or filed .
#Text=Ask your breeder or check the AKC website to see if your dog has been registered .
